[slide]
title=You still need to know SQL


[slide]
title=Terminology
markdown : '''
- Postgres is one of the most popular and powerful databases systems out there.

- It runs the SQL programming language

- All versions (dialects) of SQL are about ~90% the same, so if you learn one,
  you'll be able to use others.

### KEY TERMS
* SQL - the programming language for talking to databases
* Sqlite - the simple, limited version of SQL that we've been using thus-far
* Postgres - a database management system ("DBMS") that uses SQL
* MySQL - another popular database and SQL dialect (bought by Oracle)
* MS SQL - another popular database and SQL dialect (by Microsoft)
'''


[slide]
title=DB Structure
markdown : '''
Databases have labeled columns, and thousands (or millions) of rows.

We use the word "schema" to describe these labels and datatypes, or "shape" of
your data. When we talk about schema, we are talking about the tables column
types available.

### KEY TERMS
* database - how web apps store lots and lots of data
* schema - a common and flexible term that more or less means the shape or
  layout of your database
* table - a named collection of data
* row - a single item of data
* column - a single column of data
'''


[slide]
title=DBs are kinda like Excel
markdown : '''

This is a very rough analogy, but maybe this will help...

| SQL term      | Excel         |
| ------------- |--------------:|
| database      | .xlsx file    |
| table         | worksheet     |
| column        | column        |
| row           | row           |

'''


